ountry|Montenegro}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Morocco}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Former French colony.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Mozambique}}\n| LHT\n|\n| Portuguese colony until 1975.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Myanmar}}\n| RHT \n| 1970\n| Part of British India until 1948. Switched to RHT in 1970.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Netherlands}}\n| RHT\n| 1906<ref name=\"NED\">{{cite web|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/economie/de-claim-links-rijden~a358071/|title=De Claim links rijden|work=De Volkskrant|language=nl|author=Peter van Ammelrooy|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n| Includes [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Sint Maarten]], and Aruba\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Namibia}}\n| LHT\n| 1918\n| When South Africa occupied [[German South West Africa]] in 1920, it switched to LHT. Administered by South Africa 1920\u20131990.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Nauru}}\n| LHT\n| 1918\n|This island nation was administered by Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom until 1968. \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Nepal}}\n| LHT\n| \n| Shares land border with LHT India.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|New Zealand}}\n| LHT<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.legislation.govt.nz/regulation/public/2004/0427/latest/DLM302188.html?search=qs_all%40act%40bill%40regulation_left+side+road_resel&p=1|title= 2.1 \"Keeping Left\" \u2013 Land Transport (Road User) Rule 2004 \u2013 New Zealand Legislation |publisher= New Zealand Government |accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref>\n|\n| This Pacific island, including territories [[Niue]] and [[Cook Islands]], were former British colonies.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Nicaragua}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Niger}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Part of French West Africa before 1958.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Nigeria}}\n| RHT\n| 1972\n| British colony until 1960. Switched to RHT of being surrounded by neighbouring former French colonies.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|North Macedonia}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Norway}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Oman}}\n| RHT<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=8 August 2006|publisher=Foreign & Commonwealth Office (fco.gov.uk)|title=Travel advice by country, Oman|url=http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travelling-and-living-overseas/travel-advice-by-country/middle-east-north-africa/oman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408184423/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travelling-and-living-overseas/travel-advice-by-country/middle-east-north-africa/oman|archivedate=8 April 2008}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Pakistan}}\n| LHT\n|  \n| Part of British India before 1947.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Palau}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Palestinian National Authority}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Panama}}\n| RHT\n|1943\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Papua New Guinea}}\n| LHT\n| \n| After Australia occupied [[German New Guinea]] during World War I, it switched to LHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Paraguay}}\n| RHT\n| 1945\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Peru}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Philippines}}\n| RHT\n| 1946<ref name=\"E.O. 34 1945\"/>\n| Was LHT during the [[Captaincy General of the Philippines|Spanish]] and [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|American]] colonial periods. While Philippines switched to RHT during [[Battle of Manila (1945)|Battle of Manila]] in 1945,[[Philippine National Railways]] switched to RHT in 2010.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Poland}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Portugal}}\n| RHT<ref name=\"basement\"/>\n| 1928\n| Colonies [[Goa]], Macau and Mozambique, which had land borders with LHT countries, did not switch and continue to drive on the left.<ref name=\"mozrev\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=W2oaAAAAMAAJ&dq=mozambique+drive+on+left&q=%22Mozambique+one+drives+on+the+the+left%22 ''Mozambique: memoirs of a revolution''], John Paul, Penguin, 1975, page 41</ref> The [[Porto Metro]] uses RHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Qatar}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Former British protectorate. Switched to same side as neighbours.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Romania}}\n| RHT\n| 1919\n| Parts of Romania that formerly belonged to [[Austria-Hungary]] ([[Transylvania]], [[Bukovina]], parts of the [[Banat]], [[Cri\u0219ana]] and [[Maramure\u0219]]) were LHT until 1919.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Russia}}\n| RHT\n| \n|In the [[Russian Far East]] RHD vehicles are common due to the import of used cars from nearby Japan.<ref name=\"rbth.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/business/2016/08/31/russian-far-east-is-still-attached-to-japanese-cars_625665 |title=Russian Far East is still attached to Japanese cars |publisher=Russia behind the headlines |date=31 August 2016 |accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> Railway between Moscow and [[Ryazan]], [[Sormovskaya line]] in [[Nizhny Novgorod Metro]] and [[Moskva River cable car]] use LHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Rwanda}}\n| RHT<ref name=rwandaburundi/>\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n| LHT\n|\n|This Caribbean island nation was a British colony before 1967.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Saint Lucia}}\n| LHT\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | These Caribbean island-nations were British colonies before 1979.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n| LHT\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Samoa}}\n| LHT\n| 2009\n| Switched to LHT for economical reasons: to allow cheaper importation of cars from Australia, New Zealand and Japan.<ref name=basement/>\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|San Marino}}\n| RHT\n|\n|Enclaved state surrounded by Italy.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe}}\n| RHT\n| 1928\n| Portuguese colony until 1975.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Saudi Arabia}}\n| RHT\n| 1942\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Senegal}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Part of French West Africa before 1960.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Serbia}}\n| RHT\n| 1926\n| (as part of [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]]), [[Vojvodina]] was LHT while part of Austria-Hungary.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Seychelles}}\n| LHT\n|\n| This island nation was a British colony until 1976.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Sierra Leone}}\n| RHT \n| 1971<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=F80CAAAAMAAJ&q=Sierra+Leone++right-hand+traffic+on+1+March+1971.&dq=Sierra+Leone++right-hand+traffic+on+1+March+1971. ''The Rising Sun: A History of the All People's Congress Party of Sierra Leone''], A.P.C. Secretariat, 1982, page 396</ref>\n| British colony until 1961. Switched to RHT being surrounded by neighbouring former French colonies. Furthermore, it banned the importation of RHD vehicles in 2013.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/content/sierra-leone-officially-bans-right-hand-vehichles-as-hazards/1751527.html Sierra Leone Bans Right-Hand Vehicles as Hazards], [[Voice of America]], Nina de Vries, 17 September 2013</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Singapore}}\n| LHT\n|\n| This island nation was a British colony until 1963. It was also [[Singapore in Malaysia|part of Malaysia]] until 1965.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n| RHT\n| 1939\u201341\n| Switched during the German occupation of Czechoslovakia. \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Slovenia}}\n| RHT\n| 1926\n| (as part of [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]]), officially LHT from 1915 as part of [[Austria-Hungary]]. \n|- \n| {{Flagcountry|Solomon Islands}}\n| LHT\n|\n| This island nation was a British colony before 1975.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Somalia}}\n| RHT \n| \n| The former [[British Somaliland]] had LHT until it formed a union with the former [[Italian Somaliland]] which had RHT. \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|South Africa}}\n| LHT<ref>{{cite web|title=Road Rules|url=http://www.sacarrental.com/road-rules.htm|work=SACarRental.com|accessdate=15 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102054016/http://www.sacarrental.com/road-rules.htm|archive-date=2 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Driving in South Africa Information|url=http://www.drivesouthafrica.co.za/driving-information/south-africa/|work=drivesouthafrica.co.za|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>\n| \n| British colony before 1909.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|South Sudan}}\n| RHT\n| 1973\n| Then part of [[Sudan]].\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Spain}}\n| RHT\n| 1924\n| Up to the 1920s [[Barcelona]] was RHT, and [[Madrid]] was LHT until 1924. The [[Madrid Metro]] still uses LHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Sri Lanka}}\n| LHT\n|\n| Part of [[British Ceylon]] from 1815 to 1948.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Sudan}}\n| RHT\n| 1973\n| Formerly [[Anglo-Egyptian Sudan]], it switched sides 17 years later to match neighbors.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Suriname}}\n| LHT\n| 1920s\n| Dutch colony until 1975. One of the only two countries in continental America which are in LHT, the other being Guyana.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Sweden}}\n| RHT\n| 1967\n| The day of the switch (3 September) was known as ''[[Dagen H]]''. Most passenger cars were already LHD.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Switzerland}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Syria}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Was under French and Italian control.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Taiwan}}\n| RHT\n| 1946\n| Was LHT during the period of [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]]. The [[government of the Republic of China]] changed Taiwan to RHT in 1946 along with the rest of China.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lis.ly.gov.tw/lghtml/lawstat/version2/01172/0117235060800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210214228/http://lis.ly.gov.tw/lghtml/lawstat/version2/01172/0117235060800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 December 2013 |title=\u9055\u8b66\u7f70\u6cd5 (Act Governing the Punishment of Police Offences) |author=Passed by the Legislative Yuan |year=1946 |website= |accessdate=14 August 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Tajikistan}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Tanzania}}\n| LHT\n| \n| Part of the British East Africa Protectorate until 1961.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Thailand}}\n| LHT<ref name=\"basement\"/>\n| \n| One of the few non-British-colony LHT countries. Shares a long land border with RHT Myanmar Laos and Cambodia.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Togo}}\n| RHT\n|\n|Part of French West Africa until 1960.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Tonga}}\n| LHT\n|\n| British [[protectorate]] before 1970. Polynesian island nation.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n| LHT<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=c1n3oVO5Gv8C&pg=PA53&dq=Trinidad%20and%20Tobago%20drives%20on%20the%20left.#v=onepage&q=Trinidad%20and%20Tobago%20drives%20on%20the%20left. ''Trinidad and Tobago Adventure Guide''], Kathleen O'Donnell, Stassi Pefkaros, Hunter Publishing, Inc, 2000, page 53</ref>\n|\n| British colony before 1962. Caribbean island.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Tunisia}}\n| RHT\n|\n| RHT was enforced in the [[French protectorate of Tunisia]] since 1881.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Turkey}}\n| RHT\n| 1920s\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Turkmenistan}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Tuvalu}}\n| LHT\n|\n|This island nation was once a British colony until 1974.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Uganda}}\n| LHT\n| \n| Part of British [[Uganda Protectorate]] from 1894 until 1962.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Ukraine}}\n| RHT\n| 1922<ref name=\"Komunikacja.krakow.eurocity.pl\"/>\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|United Arab Emirates}}\n| RHT\n|\n| Former British protectorate. Switched to same side as neighbours.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|United Kingdom}}<br> <br> <br> <br> <br> <br> <br> <br>  {{Flagcountry|Gibraltar}}\n|LHT <br> <br> <br> <br> <br>  <br> <br> <br> <br>    RHT\n| <br> <br> <br> <br> <br>  <br>  <br> <br>  <br>  1929\n| Includes [[Crown dependencies]] [[Isle of Man]], [[Guernsey]], [[Jersey]], and [[British Overseas Territories|Overseas Territories]] [[Anguilla]], Bermuda, [[British Virgin Islands]], [[Cayman Islands]], [[Falkland Islands]], [[Montserrat]], [[Pitcairn Islands]] (unregistered), Turks and Caicos Islands, [[Saint Helena]], [[Ascension Island|Ascension]], [[Tristan da Cunha]] are all LHT. The [[Channel Islands]] (Jersey and Guernsey) drove on the right under [[German occupation of the Channel Islands|German occupation]] lasting from 1940 to 1945.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-iQNAAAAIAAJ&dq=channel+islands+drive+on+right+german+occupation&q=%22rule+of+the+road+was+changed+to+the+right%22 ''The Channel Islands War: 1940\u20131945''], Peter King, Hale, 1991, page 31</ref> <br>[[Gibraltar]] has been RHT since 1929 because of its land border with Spain.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MoAzAQAAMAAJ&dq=Rule+of+the+Road+Ordinance+Gibraltar+1929&q=%22Rule+of+the+Road+Ordinance%22 ''Colonial Reports''], Annual, Volumes 1480\u20131499, 1930, page 76</ref> The [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] is the only other overseas territory driving on the right.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|United States}}\n| RHT/LHT\n|\n| [[U.S. Virgin Islands]], like much of the Caribbean, is LHT and is the only American jurisdiction that still has LHT, because the islands drove on the left when the US purchased the former [[Danish West Indies]] in  the 1917 [[Treaty of the Danish West Indies]].\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Uruguay}}\n| RHT \n| 1945\n| Became LHT in 1918, but as in some other countries in South America, changed to RHT on 2 September 1945.<ref name=\"Autoblog\">[http://www.autoblog.com.uy/2015/08/el-dia-en-que-el-rio-de-la-plata-dejo.html El d\u00eda en que el R\u00edo de la Plata dej\u00f3 de manejar por la izquierda], Autoblog, 25 August 2015</ref> A speed limit of {{convert|30|km/h|0|abbr=on}} was observed until 30 September for safety.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Uzbekistan}}\n| RHT\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Vanuatu}}\n| RHT<ref>{{cite web| title = RHD/LHD Country Guide | publisher = toyota-gib.com |url= https://www.toyota-gib.com/eng/vehicle-sales/lhd-rhd-guide.html | accessdate=22 September 2017 }}</ref>\n|\n| Co-administrated under France and United Kingdom until 1980.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Venezuela}}\n| RHT\n|\n| \n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Vietnam}}\n| RHT\n|\n| French colony until 1945. The [[Long Bien Bridge]] uses LHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Western Sahara}}\n| RHT\n|\n|[[Spain|Spanish]] colony until the late 1900s.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Yemen}}\n| RHT\n| 1977<ref name=\"kincaid\"/>\n| [[South Yemen]], formerly the British [[colony of Aden]], changed to RHT in 1977. A series of postage stamps commemorating the event was issued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stampworld.com/en/stamps/South-Yemen/Postage%20stamps/?year=1977|title=South Yemen \u2013 Postage stamps \u2013 1977|work=stampworld.com}}</ref> At that time, [[North Yemen]] was already RHT.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Zambia}}\n| LHT\n| \n|British colony before 1964.\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Zimbabwe}}\n| LHT\n|\n|British colony before 1965.\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Blick auf A 2 bei Rastst\u00e4tte Lehrter See (2009).jpg|Right-hand traffic on the [[Bundesautobahn 2|A2]] in Germany\nFile:M25 motorway 2004-04-25.jpg|Left-hand traffic on the [[M25 motorway]] in the UK\nFile:Harcourt Road near Admiralty Centre.jpg|Hong Kong drives on the left.\nFile:Ecke K\u00e4rntnerstra\u00dfe Annagasse mit Werbetafel Tabarin und Chapeau Rouge ca 1930.jpg|Left-hand traffic in [[Vienna]], Austria circa 1930.\nFile:Gibraltar-LookLeft-right-hand traffic.jpg|Gibraltar has been RHT since 1929.\nFile:DriveLeftIRL.jpg|Sign reminding motorists to drive on the left in Ireland.\nFile:Drive-on-the-left-kent-1b.jpg|A road sign in the British county of [[Kent]] placed on the right-hand side of the road.\nFile:Fari-Wechsel.jpg|Change of traffic directions at the [[Thai\u2013Lao Friendship Bridge]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hook turn]]\n*[[Traffic-light signalling and operation]]\n*[[World Forum for Harmonization of Vehicle Regulations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=http://www.nicholashodder.com/download/leftright.kmz Google Maps placemarks of border crossings where traffic changes sides] (browser-based), also available as a [https://web.archive.org/web/20171020071550/http://www.nicholashodder.com/download/leftright.kmz Google Earth placemarks file] (requires [[Google Earth]])\n*[http://www.tramz.com/py/as.html The Extraordinary Street Railways of Asunci\u00f3n, Paraguay]\n\n{{Traffic law}}\n{{Road types}}\n\n[[Category:Chirality]]\n[[Category:Driving]]\n[[Category:Road transport]]\n[[Category:Rules of the road]]\n[[Category:Traffic law]]\n", "name_user": "Furtherthanfrappe", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Left-_and_right-hand_traffic"}
{"title_page": "East Lancashire Railway (1844\u20131859)", "text_new": "{{About|the original railway of that name|the heritage railway|East Lancashire Railway}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Short description|Railway company in England}} \n{{Infobox company\n| name = East Lancashire Railway\n| logo =\n| slogan =\n| fate = Amalgamation\n| successor = [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]\n| foundation = 24 July 1845\n| defunct = 13 May 1859\n| location = Lancashire\n| industry = [[Railway company]]\n| key_people = John Shae Perring (resident engineer)<ref>{{Cite ODNB | last1 = Boase| first1 = G. C. | authorlink = George Clement Boase|last2 = Cox | first2 = R. C. | title = Perring, John Shae (1813\u20131869) | year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21500 | format = Registration required | accessdate = 13 April 2009 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/21981 }}</ref>\n| products = <!--some of company's notable products-->\n| num_employees = <!--peak number of employees-->\n| parent =\n| subsid = <!--former subsidiaries, if any-->\n}}\nThe '''East Lancashire Railway''' operated from 1844 to 1859 in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]], England.  It began as a railway from [[Clifton, Greater Manchester|Clifton]] via [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] to [[Rawtenstall]], and during its short life grew into a complex network of lines connecting towns and cities including [[Liverpool]], [[Manchester]], [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] and [[Blackburn]].\n\nDuring a period of rapid growth the company acquired several of its competitors, including the [[Blackburn and Preston Railway]], which it purchased to gain access to Preston.  It faced competition from companies such as the [[North Union Railway]], and was involved in a notable stand-off in 1849 with the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]. Following several years of discussions, the East Lancashire Railway was in 1859 amalgamated with the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway.  Parts of the network remain in use today, and a section of the original line between Bury and Rawtenstall is now operated as a [[heritage railway]].\n\n== History ==\n=== Manchester and Bolton Railway ===\n{{Main|Manchester and Bolton Railway}}\nIn 1830, the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal|Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Company]] began to promote the construction of a railway along the line of their canal from [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]], to [[Bolton]] and Bury.<ref name=\"Hadfieldpp256257\">{{Harvnb|Hadfield|1970|pp=256\u2013257.}}</ref>  Following an [[act of parliament]] to enable them to become a railway company,<ref name=\"Hadfieldpp256257\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Paget-Tomlinson|2006|pp=148\u2013149.}}</ref> they built their line from Manchester to Bolton, although on a slightly different alignment than was first planned. This was mainly to preserve the canal for the use of mine traffic, which would not have been provided for if the canal had been infilled and replaced by a railway.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hadfield|1970|p=257.}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title = Canal at Pendleton on 19 November 1966|url=http://www.images.manchester.gov.uk/web/objects/common/webmedia.php?irn=57659 | publisher = Manchester Libraries | accessdate = 30 June 2008}}</ref>  A new Act had been required for the new alignment,<ref name=Backtrack>{{Citation | title = Expanded index and summary of Backtrack Volume 17 | url = http://www.steamindex.com/backtrak/bt17.htm#252 | publisher = www.steamindex.com | accessdate = 30 June 2008}}</ref> but due mainly to the objections of the company's engineer, the connection to Bury was never built, as it would have required a {{convert|1100|yd|m|adj=on}} tunnel on a gradient of 1&nbsp;in&nbsp;100, at the time a difficult and expensive proposition.<ref name=\"Wellsp3\">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=3.}}</ref>  The new railway therefore became known as the [[Manchester and Bolton Railway]].\n\n=== Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway ===\n{{Main|Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway}}\nOn 14 September 1843, a group of local businessmen including John Grundy, [[Thomas Wrigley]] and [[John Robinson Kay]] met at a [[public house]] in Bury<!-- Old Red Lion? --> to discuss the creation of a railway connection for the Bury and the Rossendale districts.  Their proposed railway offered better facilities than those also proposed by the [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]] (M&LR), whose planned connection at Bury would be made with their [[Heywood, Greater Manchester|Heywood]] branch line from [[Castleton, Greater Manchester|Castleton]].<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\">{{Harvnb|Broadbridge|2006|pp=18\u201319.}}</ref>  The Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway Company (MB&RR) was thus created, its purpose to build a railway from Bury to Clifton, where it would connect to the Manchester and Bolton Railway.  The company also promoted the idea of extending the line northwards to [[Rawtenstall]].<ref name=\"Wellsp3\"/>  On 4 July 1844 their [[Local and Personal Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom|private bill]]<ref>7 & 8 Vict. c.60</ref><ref name=\"Harrisonsale\">{{Citation | title = Harrison and Sale's Guide to the East Lancashire Railway | publisher = Harrison and Sale, 1 Spring Gardens | year = 1849 | location = Bury Local Library}}</ref><ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/> was granted [[Royal Assent]].  The Act authorised the company to raise \u00a3300,000, and also to borrow \u00a3100,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|300000|1844|r=-6}}|0}} and \u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100000|1844|r=-6}}|0}} respectively in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}).<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/>{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}\n\nThe land between Clifton and [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]], partly owned by the [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 13th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]], John Robinson Kay, William Grant and others, was mostly \"waste, woodland, pasture or reservoirs, except at Brookbottoms where arable land was avoided by the tunnel\".<ref name=\"Wellsp3\"/>  Strong financial support was offered to the MB&RR by local businesses, who were unhappy with the idea of the M&LR building their own railway.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  The Manchester and Leeds District Board of Trade produced a report in 1845 which gave their backing to the M&LR<ref>{{Citation | title = Parliamentary papers - Report of the Board of Trade on the Manchester and Leeds District | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NHASAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA17&dq=manchester+and+leeds+railway+bury | publisher = HMSO | year = 1849 | page = 17 | accessdate = 13 April 2009}}</ref> and the line was sanctioned in 1846, however the MB&RR project was unaffected by this connection.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>\n\n[[File:SirCharlesPasley.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Inspector-General of railways Sir [[Charles Pasley]] surveyed the line between Clifton Junction and Rawtenstall, and was reported to be \"highly pleased\".<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/>]]\nManchester contractors Pauling & Henfry, who tendered \u00a3167,529 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|167529|1844}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}),{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} were in May 1844 awarded two contracts to build the Clifton to Bury and Bury to Rawtenstall sections of the new railway.<ref name=\"Wellspp34\">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|pp=3\u20134.}}</ref>  The work was sub-let to smaller contractors and began quickly; in July 1844 the ''Manchester Guardian'' wrote a favourable report on the works.  However, a shortage of workers in 1845 (reflecting the amount of railway construction underway at that time) meant that some men were asked to work on Sundays, resulting in some being charged with [[Sabbath breaking|breaking the Sabbath]].  Further difficulties prompted the dismissal of the original contractors, their place being taken by John Waring.<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/>\n\n[[File:East lancashire railway bury to rawtenstall gradient.svg|thumb|300px|right|A graph of the gradient between Bury and Rawtenstall]]\n[[File:East lancashire railway map.svg|thumb|right|300px|A map of the East Lancashire Railway network before its amalgamation with the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]]]\nThe railway ran north from Clifton through a cutting at [[Outwood, Greater Manchester|Outwood]].  This required the removal of about {{convert|600000|cuyd|m3}} of earth.<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\">{{Citation | title = Opening of the East Lancashire Railway, yesterday | url = http://summerseat.ourwardfamily.com/e_l_r__opening_article.htm | date = 26 September 1846 | publisher = The Preston Chronicle and Lancashire Advertiser | access-date = 27 April 2009 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20080827224447/http://summerseat.ourwardfamily.com/e_l_r__opening_article.htm | archive-date = 27 August 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  It then passed north-east through [[Radcliffe Bridge railway station|Radcliffe Bridge]] and [[Withins Lane railway station|Withins station]],<ref>Withins station closed in 1851 - Wells (1995) p.&nbsp;10.</ref> and from there into [[Bury Bolton Street railway station|Bury Bolton street station]].  From Bury, it ran through [[Summerseat railway station|Summerseat]], [[Ramsbottom railway station|Ramsbottom]], [[Stubbins railway station|Stubbins]] and finally to [[Rawtenstall railway station|Rawtenstall]].  The railway climbed a constant gradient, across a mixture of viaducts, tunnels, cuttings and embankments, one of which, the mile\u2013long section from Ramsbottom to Stubbins, was substantial.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|Selby|1991|pp=5,&nbsp;10.}}</ref>  The extant [[Clifton Viaduct]] was built to cross the [[River Irwell]], which flowed {{convert|80|ft}} below, and also the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]].  Its largest span is {{convert|96|ft}} wide.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Expansion ===\nBy 1844, the [[Blackburn and Preston Railway]] (B&PR), who shared a viaduct across the [[River Ribble]] with the [[North Union Railway]] (NUR), were planning a railway from [[Blackburn]] to [[Farington]].<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/><ref>7 & 8 Vict. c.34</ref>  Following an 1845 act<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\">{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|p=13.}}</ref><ref>9 & 10 Vict. c.302</ref> the B&PR was absorbed by the MB&RR on 3 August 1846.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>  The B&PR's Act of Parliament also allowed for a connection with the proposed [[Blackburn, Burnley, Accrington and Colne Extension Railway]] (BBA&CER), which would run from [[Stubbins]] Junction to [[Accrington]], providing a direct link between Blackburn and Colne.  A second BBA&CER act allowed it to lease or sell itself to the MB&RR, and so <!-- on 24 July 1845? -->in 1845 the two companies joined.  The MB&RR later that year changed its name to the East Lancashire Railway (ELR).<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>\n\nThe following year, the ELR acquired the [[Liverpool, Ormskirk and Preston Railway]] (LO&PR),<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/><ref>9 & 10 Vict. c. 381</ref> which gave it direct access to [[Liverpool Docks]].  The LO&PR's line would run from a junction with the [[Liverpool and Bury Railway]] at Walton-on-the-Hill<!-- not the one in Surrey --> to a junction with the B&PR.  The enabling act also allowed the LO&PR to build further branch lines, and the ELR obtained further acts including one which allowed it to build a connection to [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  Following the acquisition on 3 August 1846,<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960a|pp=99\u2013100.}}</ref> a disagreement ensued over traffic priorities and arrangements for the ELR at the NUR's station in Preston.  The ELR proposed a new station and a separate line with a new crossing of the Ribble, but this proved controversial; Preston Corporation petitioned against the proposed line, producing a series of witnesses who attested to the damage they presumed would be caused by the embankment necessary for the scheme to proceed.  Several members of the corporation were also shareholders of the rival [[Fleetwood, Preston and West Riding Junction Railway]], and the petition's proposer was brother-in-law to a director of the rival [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]].  In the end the ELR won its bid, but had to landscape its embankment (which later became the dividing line between [[Avenham Park|Avenham]] and [[Miller Park, Preston|Miller]] Parks), make an ornamental arch for carriages and pedestrians crossing under the railway, and build a footbridge on the river viaduct.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|2001|pp=329\u2013330.}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the former MB&RR line from [[Clifton, Greater Manchester|Clifton]] to [[Rawtenstall]] was inaugurated on Friday 25 September 1846.  Surveyed two days earlier by the Inspector-General of railways, [[Charles Pasley]],<ref name=\"Pasley\">{{Cite ODNB | last1 = Vetch | first1 = R. H. | last2 = Sweetman | first2 = John | editor1-first = Elizabeth | editor1-last = Baigent | title = Pasley, Sir Charles William (1780\u20131861) | year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21500 | format = Registration required | accessdate = 13 April 2009 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/21499}}</ref> who was reportedly satisfied with the project,<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/> upwards of 1,000&nbsp;invitations were delivered to local people, shareholders and other interested parties.  They gathered at the new [[Manchester Victoria station|Hunts Bank station]] in Manchester.  Leaving Manchester, the train stopped near [[Philips Park, Whitefield|Philips Park]] to collect chairman John Hodges, before continuing to Radcliffe Bridge to collect more passengers.  Large crowds were gathered along the course of the railway.  In Bury, the train was extended to about 30&nbsp;carriages and three engines, and more passengers were collected before the train finished its journey in Rawtenstall.  Passengers were provided with a large meal in a closed-off section of a power-loom shed owned by John Robinson Kay.  They listened to several celebratory speeches, before re-embarking the train to head home.<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\"/>  The railway was opened to the general public on the following Monday.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=6.}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1846 the company submitted proposals for a new line from Buckley Wells (south of Bury) through [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]] and [[Prestwich]], to a new terminus at Victoria Station.  The plan did not progress any further than the initial planning stages; Whitefield and Prestwich eventually got their own railway stations in 1879.<ref>{{Harvnb|Townley|Appleton|Smith|Peden|1995|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nIn two years the ELR grew from a company authorised to build {{convert|14|mi}} of railway into one with the authority to build {{convert|50|mi}} of railway.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  In February 1848 with {{convert|24|mi}} of track open, the company reported for the week ending 5 February 1848 an annual income of \u00a3553 18s 8d (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|553.9333|1848|r=-3}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} for passengers and parcels, and \u00a3498 10s 4d for freight (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|498.5167|1848|r=-3}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}&nbsp;\u2013 almost double the previous year's income.<ref>{{Citation | title = East Lancashire Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS103317067&dyn=16!zoom_2?sw_aep=mclib | work = [[The Times]] | date = 11 February 1848 | page = 6 | issue = 19783 | volume = G | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  By March 1848 the line between Rawtenstall and [[Newchurch, Lancashire|Newchurch]] was complete, followed in June by the [[Blackburn]] to [[Accrington]] connection ({{convert|5.25|mi}}),<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\">{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|p=432.}}</ref> and, in August, the Stubbins junction to Accrington section.  The line was extended east to [[Burnley]] ({{convert|5.5|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> by September 1848, and, in February 1849, from Burnley to [[Colne]], where it made an end-on junction with the [[Leeds and Bradford Extension Railway]], providing the ELR with a connection to [[Bradford]] and [[Leeds]].\n\nThe LO&PR line to [[Lostock Hall]] ({{convert|26|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> was completed on 2 April 1849,<ref>{{Citation | title = Opening of the Liverpool, Ormskirk and Preston Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS135037059&dyn=31!xrn_16_0_CS135037059&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 3 April 1849 | work = [[The Times]] | issue = 20140 | volume = E | page = 8 | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref> and the ({{convert|3|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> extension into Preston station opened on 2 September 1850.<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960b|p=197.}}</ref>  The line ran into new platforms built on the east side of the NUR's station, which were managed and staffed by the ELR, and which had their own booking hall and entrance.  The new platforms were effectively a separate station.<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960a|p=101.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Suggitt|2003|p=59.}}</ref>\n\nMore lines followed with a connection between Newchurch and [[Bacup]] by October 1852, and the [[Ormskirk]] to [[Rainford]] [[Skelmersdale Branch]] in <!-- 1 march? -->March 1858.<ref name=\"Broadbridgep20\">{{Harvnb|Broadbridge|2006|p=20.}}</ref>  A three-mile long line to [[Tottington, Greater Manchester|Tottington]] opened in 1882 from a junction with the original MB&BR line. It was electrified in 1913 before reverting to steam in 1951.  It closed to passengers in 1952 and goods in 1963 and has since been reclaimed as a walkway.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|Selby|1991|p=6.}}</ref>\n\n=== Clifton Junction ===\nIn 1846, the [[Manchester and Bolton Railway]] (whose line the ELR used to gain access to Manchester) was taken over by the [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]],<ref>9 & 10 Vict. c.378</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|pp=145\u2013146.}}</ref> which, the following year, became part of the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] (L&YR).<ref>{{Harvnb|Awdry|1990|pp=90\u201391.}}</ref>  The ELR's expansion and the opening of new routes\u2014including an alternative route between Manchester and Leeds\u2014had caused a degree of consternation at the L&YR, but the two companies initially managed to work together successfully.\n\nAfter about three years a dispute flared up over the collection of tolls for the ELR's use of the line.  The ELR had become accustomed to running their trains on to the L&YR line and then later declaring of the number of passengers liable for a toll but, in March 1849, the L&YR insisted that ELR trains stop at Clifton so that passenger numbers and tickets could be checked by their own employees.  The ELR accused the L&YR of trying to impede their traffic, particularly as they had recently gained a connection to Bradford, in competition with the L&YR.  They stated that the L&YR had access to their accounts, and to the returns made by their staff.<ref name=\"Extraordinary\">{{Citation | title = Extraordinary Scene At A Railway Junction | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/806/402/60276180w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS136216687&dyn=4!zoom_2?sw_aep=mclib | work = [[The Times]] | date = 15 March 1849 | page = 8 | issue = 20124 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 12 March 1849, despite the presence of police from Bury and [[Pendleton, Greater Manchester|Pendleton]], the L&YR placed a large baulk of timber across the ELR's line at Clifton Junction, effectively blocking it.  Employees from both companies arrived at the scene, and a large crowd gathered to watch events unfold.  The L&YR also pulled a train past the junction, blocking the [[Railroad directions#United Kingdom|up line]] to the city.  Its engine was pointed south-east toward Manchester, available to any ELR passengers who wished to continue their journey.  An ELR train arrived from Bury, and stopped.  L&YR employees attempted to take tickets from the ELR's passengers, but were refused, as the ELR had already taken tickets at their Ringley Road station.  ELR employees then removed the baulk of timber, and in an effort to push the L&YR train out of the way, drove their train forward.  The L&YR had anticipated this, and moved another engine (taken from a L&YR train from Manchester) to the front of their Manchester-bound train.  The ELR then blocked the L&YR [[Railroad directions#United Kingdom|down line]] with another of their trains, laden with stone, moving it to a position directly abreast of the L&YR train.  The line remained completely blocked until about mid-day, with a queue of trains from both companies, and from the [[Blackburn and Darwen Railway]], building up on each side of the blockage.  The situation was eventually defused when the L&YR withdrew their train.<ref name=\"Extraordinary\"/>\n\nThe General Manager of the ELR, Richard Hacking, wrote to ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper expressing his annoyance at the L&YR's tactics.  He claimed to have received a letter from the company sent on 9 March 1849 informing him of proposed changes to operational procedures resulting from a near-collision at [[Clifton Junction]].  The first change was that ELR trains would at all times give way to L&YR trains on the Manchester and Bolton line; a stop signal was to be placed {{convert|400|yd}} along the ELR line from the junction, to be activated whenever a L&YR train was in sight.  The second change was that \"for the safety of the public\"<ref name=\"Battle\"/> all ELR trains would be required to stop before the [[Railroad switch|points]] at the junction, where all passenger tickets to Manchester would be collected by L&YR employees.  A daily return would be required of all passengers and other freight booked from Salford \"for the purpose of keeping regularly and balancing punctually the accounts of the two companies\".<ref name=\"Battle\"/>  Hacking claimed to have replied stating that the near-collision had occurred because the L&YR's engine driver had ignored a signal at Clifton Junction, and that the ELR would not accept the changes requested by the L&YR. The ELR refused to supply tickets at any point, although they considered it reasonable to supply more information on their traffic using the L&YR line.<ref name=\"Battle\">{{Citation | title = Letters to the Editor - Obstruction of East Lancashire Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS101220463&dyn=12!xrn_34_0_CS101220463&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | last = Hacking | first = Richard | date = 15 March 1849 | volume = F | page = 6 | issue = 20124 | work = [[The Times]] | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Clifton viaduct looking north.jpg|centre|700px|thumb|The disused [[Clifton Viaduct]].  It crosses the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] and the [[River Irwell]].  [[Clifton Junction]] is to the south of the viaduct.  Now a [[Listed building|Grade II listed]] structure, the bridge is presently closed to pedestrians.]]\nHacking stated that he had received a letter from the L&YR porter at Clifton requesting that all ELR trains stop at Clifton Junction so that tickets could be collected by L&YR staff, and that all ELR goods trains would have to supply invoices at the junction.  In his letter he concluded that the purpose of the L&YR's demands was to impede the flow of ELR traffic to Manchester and onwards to Yorkshire.<ref name=\"Battle\"/>\n\nHacking's account of the events of 12 March is similar to that reported by ''The Times''.  He claims to have travelled to Clifton to witness an L&YR clerk being prevented from collecting tickets, and to have then continued on another train to Manchester.  On his arrival there, he saw L&YR employees ready to pull up the rails to the ELR platform, although the rails were left intact.  He then mentions returning to Clifton after hearing that L&YR employees had recently left for the station.  He blamed the Managing Director of the L&YR, Captain Law, and Mr Blackmore, superintendent of the Bolton line, for ordering theline to be blocked with the baulk of timber.  Hacking also mentions an approaching up-train from Bolton, which on encountering the blockage apparently moved across to the down line to bypass it&nbsp;\u2013 in the face of oncoming traffic.  Expressing his shock, he claims to have ordered the ELR's stone train onto the down line, changing the signals accordingly.  Hacking's account ends by claiming that Blackmore ordered the L&YR train to move, effectively resolving the dispute.<ref name=\"Battle\"/>\n\n[[File:Elr approaching summerseat station.jpg|right|thumb|[[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 45407]] approaching Summerseat station on the [[heritage railway|heritage]] [[East Lancashire Railway]]]]\nThe matter was so serious that it was raised in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].<ref>{{Citation | title = House Of Commons | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS50626673&dyn=20!zoom_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 17 March 1849 | page = 3 | issue = 20126 | volume = A | work = [[The Times]] | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  It was eventually settled in court, with the ELR thereon making a [[pro rata]] payment according to the distance travelled on each railway.  The court also found in favour of the L&YR who had argued that the original agreement to share the line did not extend to a vastly extended ELR network.  The amount of compensation to the L&YR was left at the discretion of both companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bennett|Smith|1852|pp=573\u2013574.}}</ref>\n\nRelations between the two companies were, therefore, not entirely amicable.  In 1853 the ELR made further proposals for a new line from Clifton to Salford, roughly parallel to the L&YR line, however in 1854 an agreement between the two companies meant that the Clifton Junction to Salford line was vested jointly in both companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Townley|Appleton|Smith|Peden|1995|p=25.}}</ref>  Amalgamation had been discussed since the early 1850s and in <!-- 13 May -->1859, by an act of parliament,<ref>{{Harvnb|Rickards|1859|p=293.}}</ref> the ELR was absorbed by the L&YR.<ref name=\"Broadbridgep20\"/>\n\n=== Closure and legacy ===\n[[File:Ringley Road Station.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ringley Road railway station|Ringley Road station]] is on a popular route for pedestrians, cyclists, and horse riders]]\nFollowing the [[Beeching Axe]] parts of the ELR's network were closed.  The original MB&RR line between Clifton Junction and Bury closed in 1966 (although Radcliffe Bridge station was closed in 1958),<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=114.}}</ref> but the line between Bury and Rawtenstall continued to serve passengers until 1972 and freight until 1980.  This section is now used by the [[East Lancashire Railway]], a modern [[heritage railway]] opened in 1987.<ref>{{Citation | title = A History of the East Lancashire Railway| url = http://east-lancs-rly.co.uk/?p=history&m=43 | publisher = east-lancs-rly.co.uk | accessdate = 5 April 2009}}</ref>  The trackbed between Clifton and [[Radcliffe, Greater Manchester|Radcliffe]] now forms a part of the [[Irwell Sculpture Trail]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Irwell Sculpture Trail |url=http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf |publisher=irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk |accessdate=26 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326081658/http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf |archivedate=26 March 2009 }}</ref>  The connection from Stubbins to Accrington was closed in 1966.<ref>{{Harvnb|Butt|1995|p=118}}</ref>  The ELR line across the Ribble between Preston and [[Bamber Bridge railway station|Bamber Bridge]] was closed to passengers in 1968, and to goods four years later. The East Lancashire platforms 10\u201313 were demolished along with Butler Street Goods Yard.<ref>{{Harvnb|Suggitt|2003|p=60.}}</ref>  The line between Preston and Colne survives as the [[East Lancashire Line]], operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Northern Rail Network Map | url = http://www.northernrail.org/travel/networkmap | publisher = northernrail.org | accessdate = 26 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101129080239/http://www.northernrail.org/travel/networkmap | archive-date = 29 November 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  The [[Skelmersdale Branch]] was closed to passengers in 1956 and to all traffic seven years later,<ref>Marshall, J. (1981) ''Forgotten Railways North-West England'', David & Charles (Publishers) Ltd, Newton Abbott. {{ISBN|0-7153-8003-6}}, p.93</ref> however a proposal exists to reopen the line as far as [[Skelmersdale]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Merseyside Route Utilisation Strategy | url = http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/merseyside/merseyside%20rus%20.pdf | date = March 2009 | publisher = networkrail.co.uk | accessdate = 26 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090407121607/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/merseyside/merseyside%20rus%20.pdf | archive-date = 7 April 2009 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  Services between Liverpool and Ormskirk are now operated by [[Northern Line (Merseyrail)|Merseyrail]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Merseyrail Network Map | url = http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/information_access-guide_rail-network-map.html | publisher = merseytravel.gov.uk | accessdate = 26 April 2009|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080621063033/http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/information_access-guide_rail-network-map.html |archivedate = 21 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe ELR used a range of locomotives.  One of its earliest orders was for twelve [[Long Boiler locomotive|Long Boiler]] [[2-2-2]]s from [[Fenton, Murray and Jackson|Fenton, Craven and Company]] (at least one of these was used on the inauguration of the railway<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\"/>), but dissatisfied with the locomotives they accepted only four,<!-- (Marshall 3 p. 46) -->.  Four were diverted to the [[Leeds, Dewsbury and Manchester Railway]], and two to the [[Eastern Counties Railway]]. In 1848, the ELR's four 2-2-2s were rebuilt as [[2-4-0]]s by [[R and W Hawthorn]].  In about 1858, they were again rebuilt as [[0-6-0]]s by [[Sylvester Lees]].  Richard Walker, a director of the ELR between 1838 and 1854, was the supplier of about twenty locomotives to the company, including, in the 1850s, four 2-4-0s and several 0-6-0s.<ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\">{{Citation | title = Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway locomotives | url = http://www.steamindex.com/locotype/lyr.htm | publisher = steamindex.com | date = 28 October 2006 | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Walker, Richard & Brother]] supplied four 2-2-2 locomotives, Medusa, Hecate, Diomed and Lynx.  All were later rebuilt as a 2-4-0 [[Tank locomotive|tank engine]].  In 1847, two [[0-4-2]]s were supplied by R and W Hawthorn, rebuilt in 1868 as 2-4-0s.  In 1845 the MB&RR ordered four 0-6-0s from the [[Haigh Foundry]], and a fifth engine from Fenton, Craven and Company.  Another engine was built by Haigh in 1848.<ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\"/>\n\nThe largest ELR class was a series of outside-frame 2-4-0s with {{convert|15|x|20|in|cm|abbr=on}} cylinders and {{convert|5|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} driving wheels.  Some may have originated as 2-2-2s, and some were later rebuilt as 2-4-0 tank engines.  One was rebuilt as a 2-4-0 [[Tank locomotive#Saddle tank|saddle tank engine]].  These were among the last locomotives to be built in Bury.  Other manufacturers to supply the ELR were [[Sharp, Roberts and Company]], [[Stothert, Slaughter and Company]], and [[Beyer, Peacock and Company]].  The ELR livery for passenger locomotives was dark green with red brown frames, and polished domes and safety valves.<!-- Marshall (3 p. 52) --><ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\"/>\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n=== Station buildings ===\n[[File:Ormskirk Station.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ormskirk railway station]] in 1915]]\nStation buildings generally followed one of three designs.  The principal stations at Bury and Accrington were based on the same design by a Manchester-based firm of architects.  Most of the other stations were designed by the company's resident engineer. They were stone-built and consisted of a station master's room, adjoining a seated waiting area, a ladies waiting room and the booking office.  The third and cheapest design followed the standard design but utilised brick and timber as materials.  The platform was normally roofed.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Signals ===\nTrack signals were based on two designs\u2014station signals on posts, each post with two moveable arms\u2014and portable signals; flags were used by day, and coloured lanterns at night.  The signals on posts were patented [[railway semaphore signal|semaphore]] designs from J Stevens & Son.  Each post had two arms\u2014linked by chain to a foot control at the base\u2014which were used to alert drivers on both the up and down lines.  Each foot control was held in place by a hook on the post.<!-- source unreadable about horizontal arms - can anyone clarify?-->  An arm set at an angle would indicate that the train should approach slowly, before stopping at the station.  The same arm set vertically (and out of sight) would indicate that the train could pass through without stopping.  The posts were also illuminated to allow use at night.  Signals at Accrington station were more complex, linked to the station building with wires, and by default set at 'stop' when released.  The coloured lanterns used as portable signals were painted red on one side (stop), green on another (go slowly), and clear on the third (proceed).<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Rails ===\nThe line was [[standard gauge]] and most sections used [[Rail tracks|rails]] in {{convert|15|ft|adj=on}} lengths, each weighing 75&nbsp;lb/yard (31.1&nbsp;kg/m), fixed to wooden [[Railroad tie|sleepers]] {{convert|9|ft}} long and {{convert|3|ft}} apart.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n== Accidents ==\nIn the early history of the railways accidents were not uncommon, and the ELR was no exception.  Several incidents were reported in ''The Times''. During [[Whitsuntide]] 1849, a passenger train was in a rear-end collision with an excursion train near [[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]]. Despite efforts to protect the rear of the passenger train, another excursion train was in a rear-end collision with it.{{sfn|Hall|1990|p=25}} In January 1850, three people died when a luggage train ran into a passenger train at [[Maghull railway station]].<ref>{{Citation | title = The Late Accident On The East Lancashire  | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS68452904&dyn=31!xrn_20_0_CS68452904&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 8 January 1850 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 4 | issue = 20380 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  A serious accident occurred at Clifton Junction on 19 October 1851 when a passenger train derailed passing the points on the junction, injuring several passengers, some seriously.<ref>{{Citation | title = Serious Accident On The East Lancashire  | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS85099862&dyn=78!xrn_28_0_CS85099862&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 22 October 1851 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 5 | issue = 20939 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  In September 1866 a man died after jumping from the train from Blackburn.<ref>{{Citation | title = Fatal Accident | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS169124646&dyn=56!xrn_57_0_CS169124646&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 6 September 1866 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 10 | issue = 25596 | volume = B | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  A non-fatal collision occurred at [[Lostock Hall railway station]] in November 1876.<ref>{{Citation | title = Railway Collision | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS151959405&dyn=56!xrn_60_0_CS151959405&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 13 November 1876 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 9 | issue = 28785 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nInclement weather was also a problem; in January 1867 trains were delayed for several hours at {{stnlnk|Hoghton}} due to snow on the line,<ref>{{Citation | title = The Late Snow Storm | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS202023978&dyn=56!xrn_58_0_CS202023978&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 10 January 1867 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 12 | issue = 25704 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref> and on 30 January 1877 a heavy storm blew the roof completely away from [[Preston railway station]].<ref>{{Citation | title = The Gale. Meteorological Reports | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS101234751&dyn=71!xrn_61_0_CS101234751&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 31 January 1877 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 6 | issue = 28853 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation | last = Awdry | first = C | year=1990| title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies|location=Wellingborough| publisher=Stephens| isbn=1-85260-049-7}}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Bennett | first1 = Edmund H. | last2 = Smith | first2 = Chauncey (Edrs) | title = English Reports in Law and Equity | location = Boston |publisher=Little, Brown and Company |volume= 8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2yAwAAAAIAAJ |year=1852}} <!--ISBN N/A-->\n* {{Citation | author=Biddle, G.| year=1989| title=The Railways Around Preston - A Historical Review|series=Scenes From The Past|volume=6| publisher=Foxline Publishing| isbn=1-870119-05-3 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Broadbridge | first = Seymour | title = Studies in railway expansion and the capital market in England 1825-1873 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4-XA81esyFsC | publisher = Taylor & Francis | year = 2006 | isbn = 0-415-38216-5}}\n* {{Citation|last=Butt|first=R.V.J.|title=The Directory of Railway Stations|year=1995|publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd|isbn=1-85260-508-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Stanley |title=The Railway Detectives |year=1990 |publisher=Ian Allan |location=London |isbn=0-7110-1929-0 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Greville | first1 = M. D. | last2 = Holt | first2 = G. O. | date = February 1960a | title = Railway Development in Preston\u20141 | magazine = The Railway Magazine | volume = 106 | url = http://www.ukrailarchive.org/lancs/rm02-1960-094.PDF | issue = 706 | pages = 94\u2013101, 125 | access-date = 13 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170829075742/http://www.ukrailarchive.org/lancs/rm02-1960-094.PDF | archive-date = 29 August 2017 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Greville | first1 = M. D. | last2 = Holt | first2 = G. O. | date = March 1960b | title = Railway Development in Preston\u20142 | magazine = The Railway Magazine | volume = 106 | url = http://www.ukrailarchive.org/lancs/rm03-1960-197.PDF | issue = 707 | pages = 197\u2013203 | access-date = 13 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928001859/http://www.ukrailarchive.org/lancs/rm03-1960-197.PDF | archive-date = 28 September 2007 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{Citation |last=Hadfield |first=Charles |title=The canals of northwest england volume 2 |authorlink= Charles Hadfield (historian) |location = Newton Abbot |publisher=David and Charles limited | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P0YwAAAAMAAJ |last2= Biddle|first2= Gordon |year=1970 |isbn=0-7153-4992-9|ref={{harvid|Hadfield|1970}}}}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Hyde | first1 = John | last2 = Selby | first2 = Anne | title = East Lancashire Railway Guide Souvenir Special | publisher = Armstrong Printing and Graphics |date=March 1991 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Lewis | first = Brian | title = The middlemost and the milltowns | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3vqbJLHsbIMC | publisher = Stanford University Press | year = 2001 | isbn = 0-8047-4174-3 }}\n* {{Citation | author=Littleworth, C.| year=2002| title=Signal Boxes on Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway Lines - North-East Lancashire| publisher=Signalling Record Society| isbn=1-873228-21-X }}\n* {{Citation | author=Littleworth, C.| year=2014| title=Signal Boxes on Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway Lines - North and West of Manchester: Part Two| publisher=Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Society| isbn=978-0-9559467-6-9 }} \n* {{Citation |last=Paget-Tomlinson |first=Edward |title=The Illustrated History of Canal & River Navigations 3rd edition |publisher=Landmark Publishing Ltd |location=Ashbourne, UK |year=2006 |isbn=1-84306-207-0 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Rickards | first = George Kettilby | title = The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland (1807\u20131868/69) | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qgkbAAAAYAAJ | publisher = His Majesty's statute and law printers | year = 1859 }}\n* {{Citation | author=Rush, R.W.| year=1983| title=The East Lancashire Railway| publisher=The Oakwood Press| isbn=0-85361-295-1 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Scrivenor | first = Harry | title = The Railways of the United Kingdom | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TN1AAAAAIAAJ | publisher = Smith, Elder, and co. | year = 1849}}\n* {{Citation | last = Suggitt | first = G. | year = 2003 | title = Lost Railways of Lancashire | url = http://www.countrysidebooks.co.uk | publisher = Countryside Books, Newbury | isbn = 1-85306-801-2}}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Townley | first1 = C. H. A. | last2 = Appleton | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Smith | first3 = F. D. | last4 = Peden | first4 = J. A. | title = The Industrial Railways of Bolton, Bury and the Manchester Coalfield | publisher = Runpast Publishing | year = 1995 | isbn = 1-870754-32-8}}\n* {{Citation | first = Jeffrey | last = Wells | title = An Illustrated Historical Survey of the Railways in and Around Bury | publisher = Challenger Publications | year = 1995 | isbn = 1-899624-29-5 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lyrs.org.uk/ The Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081020051432/http://www.bleasdales.eclipse.co.uk/prestwichguide/where/history/bocj.htm The Battle of Clifton Junction]\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:East Lancashire Railway 1844-1859}}\n[[Category:Early British railway companies]]\n[[Category:Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]\n[[Category:Irwell Valley]]\n[[Category:Historic transport in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Closed railway lines in North West England]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1845]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1859]]\n[[Category:1844 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1845]]\n[[Category:1859 disestablishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the original railway of that name|the heritage railway|East Lancashire Railway}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Short description|Railway company in England}} \n{{Infobox company\n| name = East Lancashire Railway\n| logo =\n| slogan =\n| fate = Amalgamation\n| successor = [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]\n| foundation = 24 July 1845\n| defunct = 13 May 1859\n| location = Lancashire\n| industry = [[Railway company]]\n| key_people = John Shae Perring (resident engineer)<ref>{{Cite ODNB | last1 = Boase| first1 = G. C. | authorlink = George Clement Boase|last2 = Cox | first2 = R. C. | title = Perring, John Shae (1813\u20131869) | year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21500 | format = Registration required | accessdate = 13 April 2009 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/21981 }}</ref>\n| products = <!--some of company's notable products-->\n| num_employees = <!--peak number of employees-->\n| parent =\n| subsid = <!--former subsidiaries, if any-->\n}}\nThe '''East Lancashire Railway''' operated from 1844 to 1859 in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]], England.  It began as a railway from [[Clifton, Greater Manchester|Clifton]] via [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] to [[Rawtenstall]], and during its short life grew into a complex network of lines connecting towns and cities including [[Liverpool]], [[Manchester]], [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] and [[Blackburn]].\n\nDuring a period of rapid growth the company acquired several of its competitors, including the [[Blackburn and Preston Railway]], which it purchased to gain access to Preston.  It faced competition from companies such as the [[North Union Railway]], and was involved in a notable stand-off in 1849 with the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]. Following several years of discussions, the East Lancashire Railway was in 1859 amalgamated with the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway.  Parts of the network remain in use today, and a section of the original line between Bury and Rawtenstall is now operated as a [[heritage railway]].\n\n== History ==\n=== Manchester and Bolton Railway ===\n{{Main|Manchester and Bolton Railway}}\nIn 1830, the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal|Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Company]] began to promote the construction of a railway along the line of their canal from [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]], to [[Bolton]] and Bury.<ref name=\"Hadfieldpp256257\">{{Harvnb|Hadfield|1970|pp=256\u2013257.}}</ref>  Following an [[act of parliament]] to enable them to become a railway company,<ref name=\"Hadfieldpp256257\"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Paget-Tomlinson|2006|pp=148\u2013149.}}</ref> they built their line from Manchester to Bolton, although on a slightly different alignment than was first planned. This was mainly to preserve the canal for the use of mine traffic, which would not have been provided for if the canal had been infilled and replaced by a railway.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hadfield|1970|p=257.}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title = Canal at Pendleton on 19 November 1966|url=http://www.images.manchester.gov.uk/web/objects/common/webmedia.php?irn=57659 | publisher = Manchester Libraries | accessdate = 30 June 2008}}</ref>  A new Act had been required for the new alignment,<ref name=Backtrack>{{Citation | title = Expanded index and summary of Backtrack Volume 17 | url = http://www.steamindex.com/backtrak/bt17.htm#252 | publisher = www.steamindex.com | accessdate = 30 June 2008}}</ref> but due mainly to the objections of the company's engineer, the connection to Bury was never built, as it would have required a {{convert|1100|yd|m|adj=on}} tunnel on a gradient of 1&nbsp;in&nbsp;100, at the time a difficult and expensive proposition.<ref name=\"Wellsp3\">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=3.}}</ref>  The new railway therefore became known as the [[Manchester and Bolton Railway]].\n\n=== Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway ===\n{{Main|Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway}}\nOn 14 September 1843, a group of local businessmen including John Grundy, [[Thomas Wrigley]] and [[John Robinson Kay]] met at a [[public house]] in Bury<!-- Old Red Lion? --> to discuss the creation of a railway connection for the Bury and the Rossendale districts.  Their proposed railway offered better facilities than those also proposed by the [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]] (M&LR), whose planned connection at Bury would be made with their [[Heywood, Greater Manchester|Heywood]] branch line from [[Castleton, Greater Manchester|Castleton]].<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\">{{Harvnb|Broadbridge|2006|pp=18\u201319.}}</ref>  The Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway Company (MB&RR) was thus created, its purpose to build a railway from Bury to Clifton, where it would connect to the Manchester and Bolton Railway.  The company also promoted the idea of extending the line northwards to [[Rawtenstall]].<ref name=\"Wellsp3\"/>  On 4 July 1844 their [[Local and Personal Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom|private bill]]<ref>7 & 8 Vict. c.60</ref><ref name=\"Harrisonsale\">{{Citation | title = Harrison and Sale's Guide to the East Lancashire Railway | publisher = Harrison and Sale, 1 Spring Gardens | year = 1849 | location = Bury Local Library}}</ref><ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/> was granted [[Royal Assent]].  The Act authorised the company to raise \u00a3300,000, and also to borrow \u00a3100,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|300000|1844|r=-6}}|0}} and \u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|100000|1844|r=-6}}|0}} respectively in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}).<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/>{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}\n\nThe land between Clifton and [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]], partly owned by the [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 13th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]], John Robinson Kay, William Grant and others, was mostly \"waste, woodland, pasture or reservoirs, except at Brookbottoms where arable land was avoided by the tunnel\".<ref name=\"Wellsp3\"/>  Strong financial support was offered to the MB&RR by local businesses, who were unhappy with the idea of the M&LR building their own railway.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  The Manchester and Leeds District Board of Trade produced a report in 1845 which gave their backing to the M&LR<ref>{{Citation | title = Parliamentary papers - Report of the Board of Trade on the Manchester and Leeds District | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NHASAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA17&dq=manchester+and+leeds+railway+bury | publisher = HMSO | year = 1849 | page = 17 | accessdate = 13 April 2009}}</ref> and the line was sanctioned in 1846, however the MB&RR project was unaffected by this connection.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>\n\n[[File:SirCharlesPasley.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Inspector-General of railways Sir [[Charles Pasley]] surveyed the line between Clifton Junction and Rawtenstall, and was reported to be \"highly pleased\".<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/>]]\nManchester contractors Pauling & Henfry, who tendered \u00a3167,529 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|167529|1844}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}),{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} were in May 1844 awarded two contracts to build the Clifton to Bury and Bury to Rawtenstall sections of the new railway.<ref name=\"Wellspp34\">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|pp=3\u20134.}}</ref>  The work was sub-let to smaller contractors and began quickly; in July 1844 the ''Manchester Guardian'' wrote a favourable report on the works.  However, a shortage of workers in 1845 (reflecting the amount of railway construction underway at that time) meant that some men were asked to work on Sundays, resulting in some being charged with [[Sabbath breaking|breaking the Sabbath]].  Further difficulties prompted the dismissal of the original contractors, their place being taken by John Waring.<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/>\n\n[[File:East lancashire railway bury to rawtenstall gradient.svg|thumb|300px|right|A graph of the gradient between Bury and Rawtenstall]]\n[[File:East lancashire railway map.svg|thumb|right|300px|A map of the East Lancashire Railway network before its amalgamation with the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]]]\nThe railway ran north from Clifton through a cutting at [[Outwood, Greater Manchester|Outwood]].  This required the removal of about {{convert|600000|cuyd|m3}} of earth.<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\">{{Citation | title = Opening of the East Lancashire Railway, yesterday | url = http://summerseat.ourwardfamily.com/e_l_r__opening_article.htm | date = 26 September 1846 | publisher = ''The Preston Chronicle and Lancashire Advertiser | access-date = 27 April 2009 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20080827224447/http://summerseat.ourwardfamily.com/e_l_r__opening_article.htm | archive-date = 27 August 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  It then passed north-east through [[Radcliffe Bridge railway station|Radcliffe Bridge]] and [[Withins Lane railway station|Withins station]],<ref>Withins station closed in 1851 - Wells (1995) p.&nbsp;10.</ref> and from there into [[Bury Bolton Street railway station|Bury Bolton street station]].  From Bury, it ran through [[Summerseat railway station|Summerseat]], [[Ramsbottom railway station|Ramsbottom]], [[Stubbins railway station|Stubbins]] and finally to [[Rawtenstall railway station|Rawtenstall]].  The railway climbed a constant gradient, across a mixture of viaducts, tunnels, cuttings and embankments, one of which, the mile\u2013long section from Ramsbottom to Stubbins, was substantial.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|Selby|1991|pp=5,&nbsp;10.}}</ref>  The extant [[Clifton Viaduct]] was built to cross the [[River Irwell]], which flowed {{convert|80|ft}} below, and also the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]].  Its largest span is {{convert|96|ft}} wide.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Expansion ===\nBy 1844, the [[Blackburn and Preston Railway]] (B&PR), who shared a viaduct across the [[River Ribble]] with the [[North Union Railway]] (NUR), were planning a railway from [[Blackburn]] to [[Farington]].<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/><ref>7 & 8 Vict. c.34</ref>  Following an 1845 act<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\">{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|p=13.}}</ref><ref>9 & 10 Vict. c.302</ref> the B&PR was absorbed by the MB&RR on 3 August 1846.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>  The B&PR's Act of Parliament also allowed for a connection with the proposed [[Blackburn, Burnley, Accrington and Colne Extension Railway]] (BBA&CER), which would run from [[Stubbins]] Junction to [[Accrington]], providing a direct link between Blackburn and Colne.  A second BBA&CER act allowed it to lease or sell itself to the MB&RR, and so <!-- on 24 July 1845? -->in 1845 the two companies joined.  The MB&RR later that year changed its name to the East Lancashire Railway (ELR).<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>\n\nThe following year, the ELR acquired the [[Liverpool, Ormskirk and Preston Railway]] (LO&PR),<ref name=\"Scrivenorp13\"/><ref>9 & 10 Vict. c. 381</ref> which gave it direct access to [[Liverpool Docks]].  The LO&PR's line would run from a junction with the [[Liverpool and Bury Railway]] at Walton-on-the-Hill<!-- not the one in Surrey --> to a junction with the B&PR.  The enabling act also allowed the LO&PR to build further branch lines, and the ELR obtained further acts including one which allowed it to build a connection to [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]].<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  Following the acquisition on 3 August 1846,<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960a|pp=99\u2013100.}}</ref> a disagreement ensued over traffic priorities and arrangements for the ELR at the NUR's station in Preston.  The ELR proposed a new station and a separate line with a new crossing of the Ribble, but this proved controversial; Preston Corporation petitioned against the proposed line, producing a series of witnesses who attested to the damage they presumed would be caused by the embankment necessary for the scheme to proceed.  Several members of the corporation were also shareholders of the rival [[Fleetwood, Preston and West Riding Junction Railway]], and the petition's proposer was brother-in-law to a director of the rival [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]].  In the end the ELR won its bid, but had to landscape its embankment (which later became the dividing line between [[Avenham Park|Avenham]] and [[Miller Park, Preston|Miller]] Parks), make an ornamental arch for carriages and pedestrians crossing under the railway, and build a footbridge on the river viaduct.<ref>{{Harvnb|Lewis|2001|pp=329\u2013330.}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the former MB&RR line from [[Clifton, Greater Manchester|Clifton]] to [[Rawtenstall]] was inaugurated on Friday 25 September 1846.  Surveyed two days earlier by the Inspector-General of railways, [[Charles Pasley]],<ref name=\"Pasley\">{{Cite ODNB | last1 = Vetch | first1 = R. H. | last2 = Sweetman | first2 = John | editor1-first = Elizabeth | editor1-last = Baigent | title = Pasley, Sir Charles William (1780\u20131861) | year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21500 | format = Registration required | accessdate = 13 April 2009 | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/21499}}</ref> who was reportedly satisfied with the project,<ref name=\"Wellspp34\"/> upwards of 1,000&nbsp;invitations were delivered to local people, shareholders and other interested parties.  They gathered at the new [[Manchester Victoria station|Hunts Bank station]] in Manchester.  Leaving Manchester, the train stopped near [[Philips Park, Whitefield|Philips Park]] to collect chairman John Hodges, before continuing to Radcliffe Bridge to collect more passengers.  Large crowds were gathered along the course of the railway.  In Bury, the train was extended to about 30&nbsp;carriages and three engines, and more passengers were collected before the train finished its journey in Rawtenstall.  Passengers were provided with a large meal in a closed-off section of a power-loom shed owned by John Robinson Kay.  They listened to several celebratory speeches, before re-embarking the train to head home.<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\"/>  The railway was opened to the general public on the following Monday.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=6.}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1846 the company submitted proposals for a new line from Buckley Wells (south of Bury) through [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]] and [[Prestwich]], to a new terminus at Victoria Station.  The plan did not progress any further than the initial planning stages; Whitefield and Prestwich eventually got their own railway stations in 1879.<ref>{{Harvnb|Townley|Appleton|Smith|Peden|1995|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nIn two years the ELR grew from a company authorised to build {{convert|14|mi}} of railway into one with the authority to build {{convert|50|mi}} of railway.<ref name=\"Broadbridgepp1819\"/>  In February 1848 with {{convert|24|mi}} of track open, the company reported for the week ending 5 February 1848 an annual income of \u00a3553 18s 8d (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|553.9333|1848|r=-3}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} for passengers and parcels, and \u00a3498 10s 4d for freight (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|498.5167|1848|r=-3}}|0}} in {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}&nbsp;\u2013 almost double the previous year's income.<ref>{{Citation | title = East Lancashire Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS103317067&dyn=16!zoom_2?sw_aep=mclib | work = [[The Times]] | date = 11 February 1848 | page = 6 | issue = 19783 | volume = G | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  By March 1848 the line between Rawtenstall and [[Newchurch, Lancashire|Newchurch]] was complete, followed in June by the [[Blackburn]] to [[Accrington]] connection ({{convert|5.25|mi}}),<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\">{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|p=432.}}</ref> and, in August, the Stubbins junction to Accrington section.  The line was extended east to [[Burnley]] ({{convert|5.5|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> by September 1848, and, in February 1849, from Burnley to [[Colne]], where it made an end-on junction with the [[Leeds and Bradford Extension Railway]], providing the ELR with a connection to [[Bradford]] and [[Leeds]].\n\nThe LO&PR line to [[Lostock Hall]] ({{convert|26|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> was completed on 2 April 1849,<ref>{{Citation | title = Opening of the Liverpool, Ormskirk and Preston Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS135037059&dyn=31!xrn_16_0_CS135037059&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 3 April 1849 | work = [[The Times]] | issue = 20140 | volume = E | page = 8 | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref> and the ({{convert|3|mi}})<ref name=\"Scrivenorp432\"/> extension into Preston station opened on 2 September 1850.<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960b|p=197.}}</ref>  The line ran into new platforms built on the east side of the NUR's station, which were managed and staffed by the ELR, and which had their own booking hall and entrance.  The new platforms were effectively a separate station.<ref>{{Harvnb|Greville|Holt|1960a|p=101.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Suggitt|2003|p=59.}}</ref>\n\nMore lines followed with a connection between Newchurch and [[Bacup]] by October 1852, and the [[Ormskirk]] to [[Rainford]] [[Skelmersdale Branch]] in <!-- 1 march? -->March 1858.<ref name=\"Broadbridgep20\">{{Harvnb|Broadbridge|2006|p=20.}}</ref>  A three-mile long line to [[Tottington, Greater Manchester|Tottington]] opened in 1882 from a junction with the original MB&BR line. It was electrified in 1913 before reverting to steam in 1951.  It closed to passengers in 1952 and goods in 1963 and has since been reclaimed as a walkway.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hyde|Selby|1991|p=6.}}</ref>\n\n=== Clifton Junction ===\nIn 1846, the [[Manchester and Bolton Railway]] (whose line the ELR used to gain access to Manchester) was taken over by the [[Manchester and Leeds Railway]],<ref>9 & 10 Vict. c.378</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Scrivenor|1849|pp=145\u2013146.}}</ref> which, the following year, became part of the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] (L&YR).<ref>{{Harvnb|Awdry|1990|pp=90\u201391.}}</ref>  The ELR's expansion and the opening of new routes\u2014including an alternative route between Manchester and Leeds\u2014had caused a degree of consternation at the L&YR, but the two companies initially managed to work together successfully.\n\nAfter about three years a dispute flared up over the collection of tolls for the ELR's use of the line.  The ELR had become accustomed to running their trains on to the L&YR line and then later declaring of the number of passengers liable for a toll but, in March 1849, the L&YR insisted that ELR trains stop at Clifton so that passenger numbers and tickets could be checked by their own employees.  The ELR accused the L&YR of trying to impede their traffic, particularly as they had recently gained a connection to Bradford, in competition with the L&YR.  They stated that the L&YR had access to their accounts, and to the returns made by their staff.<ref name=\"Extraordinary\">{{Citation | title = Extraordinary Scene At A Railway Junction | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/806/402/60276180w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS136216687&dyn=4!zoom_2?sw_aep=mclib | work = [[The Times]] | date = 15 March 1849 | page = 8 | issue = 20124 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 12 March 1849, despite the presence of police from Bury and [[Pendleton, Greater Manchester|Pendleton]], the L&YR placed a large baulk of timber across the ELR's line at Clifton Junction, effectively blocking it.  Employees from both companies arrived at the scene, and a large crowd gathered to watch events unfold.  The L&YR also pulled a train past the junction, blocking the [[Railroad directions#United Kingdom|up line]] to the city.  Its engine was pointed south-east toward Manchester, available to any ELR passengers who wished to continue their journey.  An ELR train arrived from Bury, and stopped.  L&YR employees attempted to take tickets from the ELR's passengers, but were refused, as the ELR had already taken tickets at their Ringley Road station.  ELR employees then removed the baulk of timber, and in an effort to push the L&YR train out of the way, drove their train forward.  The L&YR had anticipated this, and moved another engine (taken from a L&YR train from Manchester) to the front of their Manchester-bound train.  The ELR then blocked the L&YR [[Railroad directions#United Kingdom|down line]] with another of their trains, laden with stone, moving it to a position directly abreast of the L&YR train.  The line remained completely blocked until about mid-day, with a queue of trains from both companies, and from the [[Blackburn and Darwen Railway]], building up on each side of the blockage.  The situation was eventually defused when the L&YR withdrew their train.<ref name=\"Extraordinary\"/>\n\nThe General Manager of the ELR, Richard Hacking, wrote to ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper expressing his annoyance at the L&YR's tactics.  He claimed to have received a letter from the company sent on 9 March 1849 informing him of proposed changes to operational procedures resulting from a near-collision at [[Clifton Junction]].  The first change was that ELR trains would at all times give way to L&YR trains on the Manchester and Bolton line; a stop signal was to be placed {{convert|400|yd}} along the ELR line from the junction, to be activated whenever a L&YR train was in sight.  The second change was that \"for the safety of the public\"<ref name=\"Battle\"/> all ELR trains would be required to stop before the [[Railroad switch|points]] at the junction, where all passenger tickets to Manchester would be collected by L&YR employees.  A daily return would be required of all passengers and other freight booked from Salford \"for the purpose of keeping regularly and balancing punctually the accounts of the two companies\".<ref name=\"Battle\"/>  Hacking claimed to have replied stating that the near-collision had occurred because the L&YR's engine driver had ignored a signal at Clifton Junction, and that the ELR would not accept the changes requested by the L&YR. The ELR refused to supply tickets at any point, although they considered it reasonable to supply more information on their traffic using the L&YR line.<ref name=\"Battle\">{{Citation | title = Letters to the Editor - Obstruction of East Lancashire Railway | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS101220463&dyn=12!xrn_34_0_CS101220463&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | last = Hacking | first = Richard | date = 15 March 1849 | volume = F | page = 6 | issue = 20124 | work = [[The Times]] | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Clifton viaduct looking north.jpg|centre|700px|thumb|The disused [[Clifton Viaduct]].  It crosses the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] and the [[River Irwell]].  [[Clifton Junction]] is to the south of the viaduct.  Now a [[Listed building|Grade II listed]] structure, the bridge is presently closed to pedestrians.]]\nHacking stated that he had received a letter from the L&YR porter at Clifton requesting that all ELR trains stop at Clifton Junction so that tickets could be collected by L&YR staff, and that all ELR goods trains would have to supply invoices at the junction.  In his letter he concluded that the purpose of the L&YR's demands was to impede the flow of ELR traffic to Manchester and onwards to Yorkshire.<ref name=\"Battle\"/>\n\nHacking's account of the events of 12 March is similar to that reported by ''The Times''.  He claims to have travelled to Clifton to witness an L&YR clerk being prevented from collecting tickets, and to have then continued on another train to Manchester.  On his arrival there, he saw L&YR employees ready to pull up the rails to the ELR platform, although the rails were left intact.  He then mentions returning to Clifton after hearing that L&YR employees had recently left for the station.  He blamed the Managing Director of the L&YR, Captain Law, and Mr Blackmore, superintendent of the Bolton line, for ordering theline to be blocked with the baulk of timber.  Hacking also mentions an approaching up-train from Bolton, which on encountering the blockage apparently moved across to the down line to bypass it&nbsp;\u2013 in the face of oncoming traffic.  Expressing his shock, he claims to have ordered the ELR's stone train onto the down line, changing the signals accordingly.  Hacking's account ends by claiming that Blackmore ordered the L&YR train to move, effectively resolving the dispute.<ref name=\"Battle\"/>\n\n[[File:Elr approaching summerseat station.jpg|right|thumb|[[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 45407]] approaching Summerseat station on the [[heritage railway|heritage]] [[East Lancashire Railway]]]]\nThe matter was so serious that it was raised in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].<ref>{{Citation | title = House Of Commons | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS50626673&dyn=20!zoom_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 17 March 1849 | page = 3 | issue = 20126 | volume = A | work = [[The Times]] | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  It was eventually settled in court, with the ELR thereon making a [[pro rata]] payment according to the distance travelled on each railway.  The court also found in favour of the L&YR who had argued that the original agreement to share the line did not extend to a vastly extended ELR network.  The amount of compensation to the L&YR was left at the discretion of both companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bennett|Smith|1852|pp=573\u2013574.}}</ref>\n\nRelations between the two companies were, therefore, not entirely amicable.  In 1853 the ELR made further proposals for a new line from Clifton to Salford, roughly parallel to the L&YR line, however in 1854 an agreement between the two companies meant that the Clifton Junction to Salford line was vested jointly in both companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Townley|Appleton|Smith|Peden|1995|p=25.}}</ref>  Amalgamation had been discussed since the early 1850s and in <!-- 13 May -->1859, by an act of parliament,<ref>{{Harvnb|Rickards|1859|p=293.}}</ref> the ELR was absorbed by the L&YR.<ref name=\"Broadbridgep20\"/>\n\n=== Closure and legacy ===\n[[File:Ringley Road Station.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ringley Road railway station|Ringley Road station]] is on a popular route for pedestrians, cyclists, and horse riders]]\nFollowing the [[Beeching Axe]] parts of the ELR's network were closed.  The original MB&RR line between Clifton Junction and Bury closed in 1966 (although Radcliffe Bridge station was closed in 1958),<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=114.}}</ref> but the line between Bury and Rawtenstall continued to serve passengers until 1972 and freight until 1980.  This section is now used by the [[East Lancashire Railway]], a modern [[heritage railway]] opened in 1987.<ref>{{Citation | title = A History of the East Lancashire Railway| url = http://east-lancs-rly.co.uk/?p=history&m=43 | publisher = east-lancs-rly.co.uk | accessdate = 5 April 2009}}</ref>  The trackbed between Clifton and [[Radcliffe, Greater Manchester|Radcliffe]] now forms a part of the [[Irwell Sculpture Trail]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Irwell Sculpture Trail |url=http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf |publisher=irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk |accessdate=26 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326081658/http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf |archivedate=26 March 2009 }}</ref>  The connection from Stubbins to Accrington was closed in 1966.<ref>{{Harvnb|Butt|1995|p=118}}</ref>  The ELR line across the Ribble between Preston and [[Bamber Bridge railway station|Bamber Bridge]] was closed to passengers in 1968, and to goods four years later. The East Lancashire platforms 10\u201313 were demolished along with Butler Street Goods Yard.<ref>{{Harvnb|Suggitt|2003|p=60.}}</ref>  The line between Preston and Colne survives as the [[East Lancashire Line]], operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Northern Rail Network Map | url = http://www.northernrail.org/travel/networkmap | publisher = northernrail.org | accessdate = 26 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101129080239/http://www.northernrail.org/travel/networkmap | archive-date = 29 November 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  The [[Skelmersdale Branch]] was closed to passengers in 1956 and to all traffic seven years later,<ref>Marshall, J. (1981) ''Forgotten Railways North-West England'', David & Charles (Publishers) Ltd, Newton Abbott. {{ISBN|0-7153-8003-6}}, p.93</ref> however a proposal exists to reopen the line as far as [[Skelmersdale]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Merseyside Route Utilisation Strategy | url = http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/merseyside/merseyside%20rus%20.pdf | date = March 2009 | publisher = networkrail.co.uk | accessdate = 26 April 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090407121607/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/merseyside/merseyside%20rus%20.pdf | archive-date = 7 April 2009 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  Services between Liverpool and Ormskirk are now operated by [[Northern Line (Merseyrail)|Merseyrail]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Merseyrail Network Map | url = http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/information_access-guide_rail-network-map.html | publisher = merseytravel.gov.uk | accessdate = 26 April 2009|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080621063033/http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/information_access-guide_rail-network-map.html |archivedate = 21 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe ELR used a range of locomotives.  One of its earliest orders was for twelve [[Long Boiler locomotive|Long Boiler]] [[2-2-2]]s from [[Fenton, Murray and Jackson|Fenton, Craven and Company]] (at least one of these was used on the inauguration of the railway<ref name=\"Prestonchronicle\"/>), but dissatisfied with the locomotives they accepted only four,<!-- (Marshall 3 p. 46) -->.  Four were diverted to the [[Leeds, Dewsbury and Manchester Railway]], and two to the [[Eastern Counties Railway]]. In 1848, the ELR's four 2-2-2s were rebuilt as [[2-4-0]]s by [[R and W Hawthorn]].  In about 1858, they were again rebuilt as [[0-6-0]]s by [[Sylvester Lees]].  Richard Walker, a director of the ELR between 1838 and 1854, was the supplier of about twenty locomotives to the company, including, in the 1850s, four 2-4-0s and several 0-6-0s.<ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\">{{Citation | title = Lancashire & Yorkshire Railway locomotives | url = http://www.steamindex.com/locotype/lyr.htm | publisher = steamindex.com | date = 28 October 2006 | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Walker, Richard & Brother]] supplied four 2-2-2 locomotives, Medusa, Hecate, Diomed and Lynx.  All were later rebuilt as a 2-4-0 [[Tank locomotive|tank engine]].  In 1847, two [[0-4-2]]s were supplied by R and W Hawthorn, rebuilt in 1868 as 2-4-0s.  In 1845 the MB&RR ordered four 0-6-0s from the [[Haigh Foundry]], and a fifth engine from Fenton, Craven and Company.  Another engine was built by Haigh in 1848.<ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\"/>\n\nThe largest ELR class was a series of outside-frame 2-4-0s with {{convert|15|x|20|in|cm|abbr=on}} cylinders and {{convert|5|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}} driving wheels.  Some may have originated as 2-2-2s, and some were later rebuilt as 2-4-0 tank engines.  One was rebuilt as a 2-4-0 [[Tank locomotive#Saddle tank|saddle tank engine]].  These were among the last locomotives to be built in Bury.  Other manufacturers to supply the ELR were [[Sharp, Roberts and Company]], [[Stothert, Slaughter and Company]], and [[Beyer, Peacock and Company]].  The ELR livery for passenger locomotives was dark green with red brown frames, and polished domes and safety valves.<!-- Marshall (3 p. 52) --><ref name=\"steamindexl&yr\"/>\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n=== Station buildings ===\n[[File:Ormskirk Station.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ormskirk railway station]] in 1915]]\nStation buildings generally followed one of three designs.  The principal stations at Bury and Accrington were based on the same design by a Manchester-based firm of architects.  Most of the other stations were designed by the company's resident engineer. They were stone-built and consisted of a station master's room, adjoining a seated waiting area, a ladies waiting room and the booking office.  The third and cheapest design followed the standard design but utilised brick and timber as materials.  The platform was normally roofed.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Signals ===\nTrack signals were based on two designs\u2014station signals on posts, each post with two moveable arms\u2014and portable signals; flags were used by day, and coloured lanterns at night.  The signals on posts were patented [[railway semaphore signal|semaphore]] designs from J Stevens & Son.  Each post had two arms\u2014linked by chain to a foot control at the base\u2014which were used to alert drivers on both the up and down lines.  Each foot control was held in place by a hook on the post.<!-- source unreadable about horizontal arms - can anyone clarify?-->  An arm set at an angle would indicate that the train should approach slowly, before stopping at the station.  The same arm set vertically (and out of sight) would indicate that the train could pass through without stopping.  The posts were also illuminated to allow use at night.  Signals at Accrington station were more complex, linked to the station building with wires, and by default set at 'stop' when released.  The coloured lanterns used as portable signals were painted red on one side (stop), green on another (go slowly), and clear on the third (proceed).<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n=== Rails ===\nThe line was [[standard gauge]] and most sections used [[Rail tracks|rails]] in {{convert|15|ft|adj=on}} lengths, each weighing 75&nbsp;lb/yard (31.1&nbsp;kg/m), fixed to wooden [[Railroad tie|sleepers]] {{convert|9|ft}} long and {{convert|3|ft}} apart.<ref name=\"Harrisonsale\"/>\n\n== Accidents ==\nIn the early history of the railways accidents were not uncommon, and the ELR was no exception.  Several incidents were reported in ''The Times''. During [[Whitsuntide]] 1849, a passenger train was in a rear-end collision with an excursion train near [[Burnley]], [[Lancashire]]. Despite efforts to protect the rear of the passenger train, another excursion train was in a rear-end collision with it.{{sfn|Hall|1990|p=25}} In January 1850, three people died when a luggage train ran into a passenger train at [[Maghull railway station]].<ref>{{Citation | title = The Late Accident On The East Lancashire  | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS68452904&dyn=31!xrn_20_0_CS68452904&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 8 January 1850 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 4 | issue = 20380 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  A serious accident occurred at Clifton Junction on 19 October 1851 when a passenger train derailed passing the points on the junction, injuring several passengers, some seriously.<ref>{{Citation | title = Serious Accident On The East Lancashire  | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS85099862&dyn=78!xrn_28_0_CS85099862&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 22 October 1851 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 5 | issue = 20939 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  In September 1866 a man died after jumping from the train from Blackburn.<ref>{{Citation | title = Fatal Accident | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS169124646&dyn=56!xrn_57_0_CS169124646&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 6 September 1866 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 10 | issue = 25596 | volume = B | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>  A non-fatal collision occurred at [[Lostock Hall railway station]] in November 1876.<ref>{{Citation | title = Railway Collision | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS151959405&dyn=56!xrn_60_0_CS151959405&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 13 November 1876 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 9 | issue = 28785 | volume = F | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nInclement weather was also a problem; in January 1867 trains were delayed for several hours at {{stnlnk|Hoghton}} due to snow on the line,<ref>{{Citation | title = The Late Snow Storm | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS202023978&dyn=56!xrn_58_0_CS202023978&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 10 January 1867 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 12 | issue = 25704 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref> and on 30 January 1877 a heavy storm blew the roof completely away from [[Preston railway station]].<ref>{{Citation | title = The Gale. Meteorological Reports | url = http://infotrac.galegroup.com/itw/infomark/885/935/60236960w16/purl=rc1_TTDA_0_CS101234751&dyn=71!xrn_61_0_CS101234751&hst_1?sw_aep=mclib | date = 31 January 1877 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |page = 6 | issue = 28853 | volume = D | accessdate = 14 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation | last = Awdry | first = C | year=1990| title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies|location=Wellingborough| publisher=Stephens| isbn=1-85260-049-7}}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Bennett | first1 = Edmund H. | last2 = Smith | first2 = Chauncey (Edrs) | title = English Reports in Law and Equity | location = Boston |publisher=Little, Brown and Company |volume= 8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2yAwAAAAIAAJ |year=1852}} <!--ISBN N/A-->\n* {{Citation | author=Biddle, G.| year=1989| title=The Railways Around Preston - A Historical Review|series=Scenes From The Past|volume=6| publisher=Foxline Publishing| isbn=1-870119-05-3 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Broadbridge | first = Seymour | title = Studies in railway expansion and the capital market in England 1825-1873 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4-XA81esyFsC | publisher = Taylor & Francis | year = 2006 | isbn = 0-415-38216-5}}\n* {{Citation|last=Butt|first=R.V.J.|title=The Directory of Railway Stations|year=1995|publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd|isbn=1-85260-508-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hall |first=Stanley |title=The Railway Detectives |year=1990 |publisher=Ian Allan |location=London |isbn=0-7110-1929-0 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Citation | last1 = Greville | first1 = M. D. | last2 = Holt | first2 = G. O. | date = February 1960a | title = Railway Development in Preston\u20141 | magazine = The Railway Magazine | volume = 106 | url = http://www.ukrailarchive.org